bug.short_desc: Greek capital letters with psili: diacritical mark is displayed incorrect

assigned_to.name: Nobody; OK to take it and work on it

long_desc.thetext:
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; rv:2.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/4.0 Build Identifier: 6.1.7601
With some fonts (tested Cambria, Droid Serif, Georgia and Liberation Serif) greek capital letters which have a smooth breathing mark (so called psili; http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smooth_breathing) the diacritical mark is displayed on the right side of the letter instead of the left side. However, this effects only some fonts. With the above mentioned ones I can reproduce the bug. With Times New Roman and Linux Libertine the letters are rendered correct.
View this sample page http://isaac.aquilatech.org/onlinebibel/markuptest/interlinear_test.html with different browsers. I tested it with Firefox 4, Opera 10, Chrome 11, Safari 5 and Internet Explorer 9. Firefox is the onl one who fails in this task.
Reproducible: Always
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Open http://isaac.aquilatech.org/onlinebibel/markuptest/interlinear_test.html 2. Look at the greek capital letters with the psili (last line) Actual Results: The diacritical mark is rendered on the right side of the capital letter.
Expected Results: The diacritical mark should have been rendered on the left side of the capital letter.

Regression Range : works: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US; rv:1.9.3a3) Gecko/20100315 MozillaDeveloperPreview/3.7a3 broken: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US; rv:1.9.3a4pre) Gecko/20100316 Minefield/3.7a4pre pushlog: http://hg.mozilla.org/mozilla-central/pushloghtml?fromchange=148b45c740fa&tochange=050887c64183

Could you please provide a screenshot to show the rendering you get? My current guess is that the "problem" fonts do not actually support the characters concerned, so you're getting fallback to a different font where the diacritic is placed to the right side. If we can confirm what's happening, perhaps we can adjust the font-matching behavior to prefer a better font for this range.
Created attachment 524407 This screenshot shows the rendering bug
Created attachment 524408 Chrome 10 Screenshot: No rendering bug
Created attachment 524409 Word 2010 has also no problem with the font (Cambria)

I attached three screenshots of three applications: - Firefox 4 (with the rendering bug) - Chrome 10 (displays the glyphs correct) - Word 2010 (has no problem with the font either)
I don't think your guess is right. I tested the font and this specific characters in many browsers and text processing applications and Firefox 4 is the only one that has the bug. Also, at work, where I have Windows Vista Business SP2 (x86) installed I noticed that the bug is not there (same browser). Here at home I'm using Windows 7 Professional SP1 (x86)
